   "source": [
    "## Why Pandas?\n",
    "Pandas is a Python library used for working with datasets. It does that by helping us make sense of DataFrames, which are a form of two-dimensional structured data, like a table with columns and rows. It provides many libraries which ML/DS uses in python to analyze, manipulate and get data ready for machine learning.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Why its chosen?\n",
    "- Its simple to use\n",
    "- Integrated with many other DS/ML python tools\n",
    "- Often times you get your data in format that isn't quite ready for machine Learning; so it helps you get your data ready for ML\n",
    "\n",
    "## What we'll cover?\n",
    "- Most useful functions\n",
    "- Pandas Data types\n",
    "- Importing and exporting data\n",
    "- Describing data, viewing and selecting data\n",
    "- Manipulating data\n",
    "\n",
    "## Where to get help?\n",
    "- Follow along the notebook\n",
    "- Try it for yourself (**very important**)\n",
    "- Search for it\n",
    "- Try again (**very important**)\n",
    "- **Ask**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The two main data structures(datatypes) in the pandas library are \n",
    "- **Series** and **DataFrame**.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Pandas Series**: A Series is a one-dimensional labeled array capable of holding any data type (integers, strings, floats, etc.). \n",
    "\n",
    "- **Dimensions**: 1D.\n",
    "- **Analogy**: Similar to a single column in an Excel spreadsheet or a Python list with labels.\n",
    "- **Key Feature**: Every element has an associated label called an index.\n",
    "\n",
    "Read more: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.Series.html"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Tabular data\n",
    "- **Series**"
